>

  <p>
    My name is Aaron Bollinger, and I am not a critic. I have no film school degree, no
    byline at a publication you've heard of, and no institutional credibility worth citing.
    What I do have is somewhere in the range of tens of thousands of hours spent in front
    of a screen — and the stubborn belief that at some point that has to count for something.
  </p>

  <p>
    By day I'm an insurance broker. Full time, genuinely. The Binge Bear is not a side
    hustle with ambitions of becoming a main one — it's something I do because I love it,
    because I've always loved it, and because after a lifetime of consuming film and
    television I figured I might as well do something productive with the opinions that
    were going to exist in my head regardless.
  </p>

  <h2>Since the age of five</h2>

  <p>
    I was glued to the TV before I could fully explain what I was watching. That never
    really stopped. I grew up on it, stayed on it, and built my leisure life around it.
    Movies, prestige drama, reality television, documentaries, sports — if it plays on a
    screen I have probably watched more of it than most people you know. I also read. I
    follow sport closely. But above all else, it's always been the films and the shows.
    That's the through-line.
  </p>

  <h2>What this actually is</h2>

  <p>
    The Binge Bear is one person's honest account of what's worth your time and what
    isn't. I'm not trying to be Roger Ebert. I'm not trying to build a media company.
    I'm a standalone writer putting real watches and real reactions into words, for anyone
    who finds that useful when deciding how to spend their evening.
  </p>

  <p>
    My reviews stay out of politics. I'm not here to tell you what a film means about
    society or use a TV show as a vessel for commentary on the current moment. I watch
    things and I tell you whether they're good. Whether the writing holds up, whether the
    performances land, whether you'll feel something by the end of it. That's the job.
  </p>

  <h2>Why trust me</h2>

  <p>
    Honestly — you don't have to. No one is making you. But if you're the kind of person
    who's ever wanted a recommendation from someone who has genuinely seen nearly
    everything, has no agenda, takes no advertising money, and will tell you plainly when
    something is a waste of two hours — then we're probably going to get along fine.
  </p>

  <p>
    Questions, disagreements, and recommendations are always welcome at
    <a href="mailto:hello@bingebear.com">hello@bingebear.com</a>. Especially
    disagreements.
  </p>

</Layout>